    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Elderberry Gummies for Adults</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do elderberry gummies actually work for adults?</summary><p>A 2019 meta-analysis of 4 RCTs found elderberry significantly reduced cold duration (by 2 days) and severity. Most effective when started within 48 hours of symptom onset. Active anthocyanins block viral entry and stimulate cytokine-mediated immune response.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much elderberry should adults take daily?</summary><p>100-200mg concentrated extract (equiv. 500-1,000mg raw fruit) once daily for prevention. During active symptoms, some protocols suggest 2-4 servings daily for 3-5 days. Follow product-specific dosing. More is not necessarily better.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is the difference between elderberry for kids and adults?</summary><p>Adult formulas have higher extract doses (100-200mg vs. 50-100mg), adult-strength cofactors (zinc, vitamin C), and larger gummy sizes. Adults should always use adult-formulated products for adequate dosing per body weight.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take elderberry gummies every day?</summary><p>Daily use during cold/flu season (October-April) is supported by clinical trials of up to 5 months. Some practitioners recommend seasonal cycling rather than year-round use. Prolonged immune stimulation beyond 5 months is not well-studied.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Should I take elderberry with vitamin C and zinc?</summary><p>Yes. Each targets a different immune pathway: elderberry (viral entry blockade + cytokines), vitamin C (neutrophil function + antioxidant), zinc (viral replication inhibition + T-cell maturation). Many premium formulas combine all three.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Are elderberry gummies safe for adults with autoimmune conditions?</summary><p>Caution required. Elderberry stimulates cytokines (IL-1, IL-6, TNF-alpha), which could theoretically worsen autoimmune conditions with an already overactive immune system. No direct evidence of harm, but consult your rheumatologist or immunologist before use.</p></details>

